    <h1>Listing Hijacking</h1>
    <p class="description">When an unauthorized party claims ownership of or makes unauthorized edits to your <strong>Google Business Profile</strong> — changing your phone number, hours, or address to redirect customers to competitors or suppress your listing entirely.</p>
    <div class="post-meta">
      <div class="meta-author">
        <div class="meta-avatar">AVR</div>
        <div class="meta-author-info">
          <span class="meta-author-name"><a href="/authors/akshay-vr/">Akshay VR</a></span>
          <span class="meta-author-role">Marketing Head · theStacc</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Published</span><span class="meta-value">Jul 2026</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Read</span><span class="meta-value">7 min</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">GBP Hijacking, Profile Takeover</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Listing hijacking</strong> occurs when someone other than the legitimate business owner claims ownership of or makes unauthorized modifications to a Google Business Profile (GBP). The attacker can change the business phone number, address, hours, or category — redirecting customers who find the listing in local search to a competitor or to a dead end. Unmonitored or unverified GBP listings are the most vulnerable.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platform affected</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Business Profile</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recovery time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Days to weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">For any business that depends on local search — a restaurant, a plumber, a dental practice, a law firm — a hijacked listing can mean days or weeks of lost calls, misdirected customers, and revenue damage while you work through Google's recovery process. Prevention takes 10 minutes. Recovery can take weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is listing hijacking?</h2>
        <p>Listing hijacking is an attack on your Google Business Profile that exploits gaps in Google's identity verification process. Google allows anyone to suggest edits to a business listing and allows anyone to claim ownership of an unverified or abandoned listing.</p>
        <p>Attackers exploit this in three main ways:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ownership claim.</strong> An attacker submits a claim saying they own the business. If your listing is unverified, Google may approve the claim automatically. The attacker now has full editing access.</li>
          <li><strong>Bulk edit spam.</strong> Attackers submit "suggest an edit" corrections (a public feature) repeatedly. Google's automated system sometimes approves these edits without manual review — changing your phone number or hours without your knowledge.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-party management access.</strong> If you previously granted an agency or contractor management access to your GBP and never revoked it, a disgruntled former partner can make changes or remove your owner access.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Who gets targeted most</div>
          <p>Listing hijacking is most common in high-value local service categories: <strong>locksmiths, plumbers, lawyers, medical practices, and multi-location restaurant chains</strong>. These businesses attract spam operators who divert calls to competing services. Multi-location businesses are particularly vulnerable because managing 20+ GBP listings manually is difficult.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why listing hijacking matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>A hijacked listing doesn't just create an embarrassing inaccuracy — it actively damages revenue in real time:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Phone calls go to competitors.</strong> The most common hijack changes the phone number. Customers who find your listing in Google Maps and call the number reach a competitor's line or a disconnected number. They rarely call back — they just call the next result.</li>
          <li><strong>Customers arrive at wrong locations.</strong> Changing the address sends customers to a competitor's location or an empty lot. For restaurants and retail, this means walk-in customers who don't return.</li>
          <li><strong>Permanent closure flags suppress ranking.</strong> Marking a business as "permanently closed" removes it from local pack results immediately. Even after reversal, listings may take days to reappear in Local Pack rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Review manipulation becomes possible.</strong> An attacker with owner-level access can respond to reviews as your business, flag legitimate reviews for removal, or post fake responses that damage brand perception.</li>
          <li><strong>Recovery is slow.</strong> Google's GBP support process for reclaiming a hijacked listing typically takes 3-14 business days. During that window, your local SEO traffic is impaired or gone.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How listing hijacking actually works</h2>
        <p>Understanding the mechanics helps you defend against them.</p>

        <h3>The ownership claim attack</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Attacker's process for ownership claim hijack</span><br>
          1. Search Google Maps for target business<br>
          2. Click "Claim this business" on an unverified listing<br>
          3. Submit false verification information<br>
          4. Google sends a postcard to the listed address — <span class="uf-old">or approves automatically</span><br>
          5. Attacker gains owner access → <span class="uf-old">changes phone, address, hours</span>
        </div>

        <h3>The bulk edit attack</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Suggest-an-edit spam attack</span><br>
          Multiple accounts submit "corrections" to your listing<br>
          Google's automated review approves after threshold reached<br>
          <span class="uf-old">Business hours changed to "Permanently closed"</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">Phone number changed to competitor's line</span><br>
          Owner receives no real-time alert → damage accumulates
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of listing hijacking attacks</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Attack type</th><th>What changes</th><th>Who does it</th><th>Recovery time</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Ownership claim</strong></td>
                <td>Full profile control</td>
                <td>Competitors, spam operators</td>
                <td>1-3 weeks via Google support</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Bulk edit spam</strong></td><td>Hours, phone, address</td><td>Competitor spam rings</td><td>Days via GBP dashboard</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Category change</strong></td><td>Primary business category</td><td>Competitors in adjacent niches</td><td>Days — instant if you catch it</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Closure flag</strong></td><td>Business status = closed</td><td>Anyone with "suggest edit" access</td><td>Hours to days</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Rogue manager</strong></td><td>Any field, incl. owner removal</td><td>Former employees or agencies</td><td>Weeks if owner access is lost</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real listing hijacking examples</h2>

        <h3>Locksmith targeted by spam operators</h3>
        <p>A locksmith in Chicago had their GBP phone number changed to a call center that redirected to an out-of-town locksmith. The business owner didn't notice for 11 days. During that window, customers who called from Google Maps reached a competitor. The business estimated losing 40-60 calls — approximately $8,000-12,000 in lost revenue — before discovering the change via a regular dashboard audit.</p>

        <h3>Multi-location restaurant chain: 60% GBP impressions lost</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant chain had 3 of its locations marked as "permanently closed" via bulk edit spam over a weekend. The listings were removed from Local Pack results for those locations within 24 hours. After recovery, the chain implemented weekly GBP audits across all locations and saw a 60% increase in GBP impressions at those locations within the first quarter — recovery combined with active optimization.</p>

        <h3>Law firm: category change buried their ranking</h3>
        <p>A personal injury law firm had their primary GBP category changed from "Personal Injury Attorney" to "General Contractor" by a competitor's spam campaign. The category mismatch removed them from Local Pack results for personal injury searches within days. Recovery required Google support intervention to restore the original category — a 5-day process.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Listing hijacking vs GBP spam — what's the difference?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Listing hijacking (against you)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Unauthorized changes to your verified listing</li>
              <li>Ownership claim by a competitor or spam operator</li>
              <li>Goal: redirect your customers or suppress your ranking</li>
              <li>You are the victim — requires active defense</li>
              <li>Google's support process needed for full recovery</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>GBP spam (by others)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Fake business listings in your service area</li>
              <li>Competitors with stuffed keywords in business name</li>
              <li>Goal: outrank legitimate businesses in Local Pack</li>
              <li>Report via "Suggest an edit" or GBP spam form</li>
              <li>Requires Google spam reporting, not support ticket</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices to prevent listing hijacking</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Verify your listing with postcard or video — not phone.</strong> Phone verification is the weakest form. Postcard or video verification creates a harder ownership record that's more difficult for attackers to dispute. If your listing is currently phone-verified only, upgrade it.</li>
          <li><strong>Enable two-factor authentication on your Google account.</strong> The Google account managing your GBP must have 2FA enabled. A compromised Google account is a direct path to listing access.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit your GBP dashboard weekly.</strong> Set a recurring calendar reminder. Check: primary category, phone number, hours, address, website URL, and the list of managers. Takes 3 minutes. Catches changes before customers do.</li>
          <li><strong>Set Google Alerts for your business name.</strong> Create a free Google Alert at google.com/alerts for your exact business name. You'll receive an email if your business name appears in new web content — which often precedes or accompanies a hijack attempt.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit manager access quarterly.</strong> Remove any former agencies, employees, or contractors from your GBP manager list. Go to GBP → Settings → Managers and remove anyone no longer working with you.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a dedicated Google account for GBP, not a personal account.</strong> If your personal Google account gets compromised, your GBP shouldn't. Keep them separate, and keep the GBP account credentials locked down.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — leaving an unverified listing unattended</div>
          <p>An unverified GBP listing is open to ownership claims from anyone. If Google has auto-generated a listing for your business and you haven't claimed it, a competitor or spam operator can claim it before you do. Search Google Maps for your business name right now. If there's a listing without a "Claimed" badge, claim it immediately — even if you weren't planning to actively use it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common listing hijacking mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring GBP dashboard notifications</strong> — Google sends emails when edits are suggested. These often get filtered to spam. Check your Google account's notification settings.</li>
          <li><strong>Granting owner access to agencies without tracking it</strong> — agencies need manager access, not owner access. Owner access means they can remove you. Always set agencies as managers, never as owners.</li>
          <li><strong>Not documenting your original listing data</strong> — before a hijack happens, screenshot your full GBP profile: NAP, category, attributes, hours. This becomes your evidence for Google support if recovery is needed.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a personal email for GBP management</strong> — personal email accounts are targeted for phishing. A dedicated Google Workspace account with strong security is significantly safer.</li>
          <li><strong>Waiting for customers to report problems</strong> — by the time a customer tells you they called a wrong number, you've already lost dozens of calls. Proactive weekly audits are the only reliable detection method.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How does listing hijacking happen?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Listing hijacking happens when a competitor, spam operator, or disgruntled party submits an ownership claim on your Google Business Profile, takes over management via Google's unverified-listing loophole, or submits bulk edits via Google Maps that pass through automated approval. Profiles left unmonitored are most vulnerable.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I know if my Google Business Profile has been hijacked?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Signs include: phone number changed to an unknown number, business hours showing as permanently closed, address pointing to a competitor's location, business name modified with added keywords or competitor branding, or ownership access revoked. Check your GBP dashboard weekly and set up Google Alerts for your business name.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What should I do if my listing is hijacked?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Immediately file an ownership claim through Google Business Profile support at support.google.com/business. Submit identity verification documents. If edits were made, use the "Suggest an edit" reversal or contact Google support directly. Document all unauthorized changes with screenshots before attempting recovery.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can a competitor hijack my Google Business Profile?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Competitors can submit fake ownership claims on unlocked or unverified GBP listings. Google's system occasionally approves these before verifying identity. This is most common in competitive local markets — legal services, plumbing, locksmiths, and medical practices see the highest rates.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How can I prevent listing hijacking?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Verify your listing via postcard or video (stronger than phone verification), enable two-factor authentication on your Google account, check your GBP dashboard weekly, set up Google Alerts for your business name, and never leave your listing unverified. Verified listings are significantly harder to hijack.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

